            "content": "# NixonNote Emergent Behavior Analysis — PRD & Technical Spec\n\n**Date**: 2026-02-13\n**Status**: Draft\n**Authors**: Emergent Behavior Analysis Agent\n\n---\n\n## Table of Contents\n\n1. [Executive Summary](#executive-summary)\n2. [System Context](#system-context)\n3. [Finding 1: Connection Pool PRAGMA Leak (CRITICAL)](#finding-1-connection-pool-pragma-leak)\n4. [Finding 2: Stale Embeddings After Note Update](#finding-2-stale-embeddings-after-note-update)\n5. [Finding 3: Voice Memo Garbage Embeddings](#finding-3-voice-memo-garbage-embeddings)\n6. [Finding 4: Background Queue Backpressure](#finding-4-background-queue-backpressure)\n7. [Finding 5: Podcast Feed Port Mismatch](#finding-5-podcast-feed-port-mismatch)\n8. [Finding 6: No Frontend Notification of AI Enrichment](#finding-6-no-frontend-notification-of-ai-enrichment)\n9. [Finding 7: Audio-Note Temporal Coupling](#finding-7-audio-note-temporal-coupling)\n10. [Finding 8: Delete Orphan Cascade](#finding-8-delete-orphan-cascade)\n11. [Finding 9: Pagination Count Mismatch](#finding-9-pagination-count-mismatch)\n12. [Finding 10: Dual AppError Response Formats](#finding-10-dual-apperror-response-formats)\n13. [Finding 11: TTS Temp File Name Collisions](#finding-11-tts-temp-file-name-collisions)\n14. [Finding 12: Approximate Date Calculation](#finding-12-approximate-date-calculation)\n15. [Priority Matrix](#priority-matrix)\n16. [Implementation Roadmap](#implementation-roadmap)\n\n---\n\n## Executive Summary\n\nAn emergent behavior analysis of the NixonNote codebase revealed **12 issues** arising from implicit interactions between components. These are not bugs in individual functions — each function works correctly in isolation. The problems emerge from the *composition* of components operating under assumptions that are never explicitly stated or enforced.\n\nThe most critical finding is a **data integrity issue**: SQLite `PRAGMA foreign_keys = ON` and `PRAGMA busy_timeout = 5000` are only set on the first connection checked out from the pool, not on subsequent connections. This means foreign key constraints are silently unenforced on most database operations, and concurrent write contention causes immediate `SQLITE_BUSY` errors instead of graceful retries.\n\n### Impact Summary\n\n| Severity | Count | Categories |\n|----------|-------|------------|\n| CRITICAL | 1 | Data integrity (foreign keys, write contention) |\n| HIGH | 2 | Data consistency (stale embeddings, garbage vectors) |\n| MEDIUM | 3 | Availability (backpressure), functionality (RSS), UX (enrichment delay) |\n| LOW | 6 | Display bugs, disk cleanup, consistency, robustness |\n\n---\n\n## System Context\n\n### Architecture Overview\n\n```\n┌──────────────────────────┐\n│   React 19 + Vite SPA    │\n│   (Bearer token auth)    │\n└──────────┬───────────────┘\n           │ HTTP/JSON\n┌──────────▼───────────────┐\n│   Axum HTTP Server       │\n│   (routes: notes, voice, │\n│    audio, chat, ingest)  │\n├──────────┬───────────────┤\n│ POST req │  Response 201 │\n│          │  (bare note)  │\n│          │               │\n│  ┌───────▼────────┐      │\n│  │ enqueue(id)    │      │\n│  │ fire-and-forget│      │\n│  └───────┬────────┘      │\n└──────────┼───────────────┘\n           │ mpsc channel (cap: 100)\n┌──────────▼───────────────┐\n│ BackgroundProcessor      │\n│ (single tokio task)      │\n│                          │\n│ ProcessNote(id):         │\n│   1. retry_transcription │\n│   2. embed_note (Ollama) │\n│   3. auto_org (Claude)   │\n│                          │\n│ GenerateAudio(ep_id):    │\n│   1. fetch notes         │\n│   2. TTS (OpenAI/Gemini) │\n│   3. ffmpeg concat       │\n│   4. update DB           │\n└──────────┬───────────────┘\n           │\n┌──────────▼───────────────┐\n│ SQLite (WAL mode)        │\n│ deadpool-sqlite pool     │\n│                          │\n│ Tables: notes, tags,     │\n│ note_tags, note_embed,   │\n│ note_links, notes_fts,   │\n│ audio_episodes,          │\n│ audio_episode_notes,     │\n│ settings, api_usage      │\n└──────────────────────────┘\n```\n\n### Key Data Flow: Note Lifecycle\n\n```\nUser creates note (POST /api/notes)\n  │\n  ├─ 1. INSERT into SQLite ───────── immediate, synchronous\n  ├─ 2. Return 201 + bare JSON ──── no title, no summary, no tags\n  ├─ 3. background.enqueue(id) ──── fire-and-forget into mpsc\n  │\n  │  [later, async, sequential]\n  │\n  ├─ 4a. retry_pending_transcription ── check audio_pending/{id}.webm\n  ├─ 4b. embed_note ─────────────────── Ollama → 768-dim vector → DB\n  └─ 4c. auto_org_note ─────────────── Claude API → title + summary + tags → DB\n\n  ❌ No notification sent to frontend when steps 4a-4c complete\n```\n\n---\n\n## Finding 1: Connection Pool PRAGMA Leak\n\n**Severity**: CRITICAL\n**Category**: Data Integrity\n**Affected files**:\n- `src/main.rs:54-60`\n- `src/db/mod.rs:7-24`\n- `src/db/mod.rs:26-33`\n\n### Problem Statement\n\nSQLite PRAGMAs `foreign_keys`, `busy_timeout`, and `journal_mode` are set via `setup_connection()` only once — on the first connection checked out from the deadpool-sqlite pool during server startup. However, `foreign_keys` and `busy_timeout` are **per-connection** settings in SQLite (not database-wide), and the pool creates new connections on demand. New connections receive SQLite's defaults: `foreign_keys = OFF` and `busy_timeout = 0`.\n\n### Root Cause\n\n```rust\n// src/main.rs:54-60\n// This only runs ONCE on the first connection:\n{\n    let conn = pool.get().await?;\n    conn.interact(|c| db::setup_connection(c))\n        .await\n        .map_err(|e| anyhow::anyhow!(\"Pool interaction error: {e}\"))??;\n}\n```\n\n```rust\n// src/db/mod.rs:7-24\n// Pool is created with NO per-connection initialization hook:\npub fn create_pool(db_path: &str) -> Result<Pool> {\n    // ... sqlite-vec auto extension ...\n    let cfg = Config::new(db_path);\n    let pool = cfg.builder(Runtime::Tokio1)?.build()?;\n    Ok(pool)\n}\n```\n\nThe `Config::builder()` API supports a `post_create` hook for per-connection initialization, but it is not used.\n\n### Impact\n\n1. **Foreign key constraints are silently disabled** on most pool connections. The `audio_episode_notes` table has `ON DELETE CASCADE` referencing both `audio_episodes` and `notes`, but this cascade only works when `PRAGMA foreign_keys = ON`. INSERT operations could create orphaned references without error (e.g., inserting a `note_tag` row referencing a non-existent `note_id`).\n\n2. **Write contention causes immediate errors** instead of graceful retries. Without `busy_timeout = 5000`, any write that encounters a WAL lock will receive an immediate `SQLITE_BUSY` error rather than retrying for up to 5 seconds. This particularly affects:\n   - Concurrent background processing and HTTP request handling\n   - Batch import operations that run many writes in quick succession\n   - The `rederive_queue` startup path that runs while HTTP requests are being served\n\n3. **The delete cascade in `queries.rs` masks the problem.** `delete_note()` manually DELETEs from `note_tags`, `note_embeddings`, and `note_links` before deleting the note itself — which is exactly what `ON DELETE CASCADE` would do if foreign keys were enabled. This manual cascade works regardless of the PRAGMA, hiding the fact that the constraint is disabled.\n\n### Evidence\n\nFrom the SQLite documentation (https://www.sqlite.org/foreignkeys.html):\n\n> Foreign key constraints are disabled by default (for backwards compatibility), so must be enabled separately for each database connection.\n\nThe `PRAGMA journal_mode = WAL` is an exception — once set, it persists for the database file. But `foreign_keys` and `busy_timeout` must be set per-connection.\n\n### Proposed Fix\n\nAdd a per-connection initialization hook to the pool builder. The deadpool-sqlite `Manager` struct can be customized, or every `pool.get()` call can be wrapped:\n\n**Option A: Wrapper function (minimal change)**\n\n```rust\n// src/db/mod.rs\npub async fn get_conn(pool: &Pool) -> Result<deadpool_sqlite::Object> {\n    let conn = pool.get().await?;\n    conn.interact(|c| {\n        c.execute_batch(\n            \"PRAGMA foreign_keys = ON;\n             PRAGMA busy_timeout = 5000;\"\n        )\n    }).await\n      .map_err(|e| anyhow::anyhow!(\"{e}\"))??;\n    Ok(conn)\n}\n```\n\nThen replace all `pool.get().await` calls with `db::get_conn(&pool).await`.\n\n**Option B: Custom pool manager (cleaner, more work)**\n\nImplement a custom `deadpool::managed::Manager` that calls `setup_connection` in `create()`.\n\n### Acceptance Criteria\n\n- [ ] Every connection from the pool has `PRAGMA foreign_keys = ON`\n- [ ] Every connection from the pool has `PRAGMA busy_timeout = 5000`\n- [ ] Integration test that verifies foreign key enforcement on a pool connection (not just the first one)\n- [ ] `setup_connection` is no longer called in `main.rs`; connection init is handled by the pool/wrapper\n\n---\n\n## Finding 2: Stale Embeddings After Note Update\n\n**Severity**: HIGH\n**Category**: Data Consistency\n**Affected files**:\n- `src/routes/notes.rs:361-397` (update_note handler)\n- `src/background/embed.rs:30-39` (has_embedding early return)\n- `src/background/auto_org.rs:75-84` (existing AI tags early return)\n\n### Problem Statement\n\nWhen a user edits a note's content via `PUT /api/notes/:id`, the handler correctly enqueues the note for re-processing. However, both `embed_note()` and `auto_org_note()` have early-return guards that skip processing if the note already has an embedding or AI tags:\n\n```rust\n// src/background/embed.rs:36-39\nif has_embedding {\n    info!(note_id, \"Note already has embedding, skipping\");\n    return Ok(());\n}\n```\n\n```rust\n// src/background/auto_org.rs:81-84\nif existing_tags.iter().any(|t| t.source == \"ai\") {\n    info!(note_id, \"Note already has AI tags, skipping\");\n    return Ok(());\n}\n```\n\nThis means **editing a note does not update its embedding vector, title, summary, or AI tags**. The data from the original content persists.\n\n### Impact\n\n1. **Semantic search diverges from content.** SQLite FTS5 is automatically updated via triggers (correct), so full-text search finds the new content. But vector similarity search uses the stale embedding from the original content, producing misranked or irrelevant results.\n\n2. **Title and summary are frozen.** If a user substantially rewrites a note, the AI-generated title and summary still reflect the original content. This is visible in the note list and side panel.\n\n3. **Tags are frozen.** A note about \"Rust async programming\" that gets rewritten to be about \"cooking recipes\" retains its \"rust\", \"async\", \"programming\" tags.\n\n### Root Cause\n\nThe early-return guards were designed for the initial processing pipeline, where notes are processed exactly once after creation. When `update_note` was later added with re-enqueue logic, the guards were not updated to handle re-processing.\n\n### Proposed Fix\n\nAdd a `force: bool` parameter to `BackgroundJob::ProcessNote`:\n\n```rust\npub enum BackgroundJob {\n    ProcessNote { note_id: i64, force: bool },\n    GenerateAudio { episode_id: i64 },\n}\n```\n\nWhen `force = true`:\n- `embed_note()` should DELETE the existing embedding before generating a new one (the `insert_embedding` function already handles the INSERT part)\n- `auto_org_note()` should DELETE existing AI tags before re-running\n\nThe `update_note` handler sends `ProcessNote { note_id: id, force: true }`, while `create_note` sends `ProcessNote { note_id: id, force: false }`.\n\n### Acceptance Criteria\n\n- [ ] Editing a note's content triggers re-embedding with the new content\n- [ ] Editing a note's content triggers re-generation of title, summary, and tags\n- [ ] The old embedding is replaced, not appended\n- [ ] The old AI tags are replaced, not accumulated\n- [ ] Creating a new note still works normally (no double-processing)\n\n---\n\n## Finding 3: Voice Memo Garbage Embeddings\n\n**Severity**: HIGH\n**Category**: Search Quality\n**Affected files**:\n- `src/routes/voice.rs:56-107` (transcribe_voice handler)\n- `src/background/mod.rs:89-119` (process_note pipeline)\n- `src/background/embed.rs:22-70` (embed_note)\n- `src/background/auto_org.rs:67-84` (auto_org_note)\n\n### Problem Statement\n\nWhen Whisper transcription fails (e.g., Osaurus is unavailable), the system:\n\n1. Creates a note with placeholder content: `\"[Voice memo - transcribing...]\"` (voice.rs:63)\n2. Saves the raw audio to `audio_pending/{id}.webm` for later retry (voice.rs:87-89)\n3. Enqueues the note for background processing (voice.rs:100)\n\nThe background processor then:\n\n1. Attempts `retry_pending_transcription` — if Whisper is still down, this fails (mod.rs:92-100)\n2. Runs `embed_note` on the placeholder text `\"[Voice memo - transcribing...]\"` (mod.rs:102-106)\n3. Runs `auto_org_note` on the placeholder text (mod.rs:108-116)\n\n### Impact\n\n- The embedding index gets a **meaningless 768-dimensional vector** encoding the string `\"[Voice memo - transcribing...]\"`. This vector will be similar to other placeholder embeddings and dissimilar to everything else, degrading vector search quality for all notes.\n- Claude will generate AI tags, title, and summary for the placeholder text — producing garbage metadata like `title: \"Voice Memo Transcription\"`, `tags: [\"voice\", \"memo\", \"transcription\"]`.\n- When transcription eventually succeeds (via a later `retry_pending_transcription` call), the note content is updated — but due to Finding 2, the **stale placeholder embedding and tags persist forever**.\n\n### Root Cause\n\nThe `process_note` pipeline always runs all three steps sequentially, regardless of whether transcription succeeded. There is no check between Step 0 (transcription retry) and Steps 1-2 (embed + auto-org) to verify that the note content is meaningful.\n\n### Proposed Fix\n\nTwo changes needed:\n\n1. **In `process_note`**: After `retry_pending_transcription`, re-read the note content. If it still equals `\"[Voice memo - transcribing...]\"`, skip `embed_note` and `auto_org_note`.\n\n2. **In `retry_pending_transcription`**: When transcription succeeds and the note content is updated, delete the existing embedding (if any) and existing AI tags, so subsequent processing generates fresh metadata. This also requires fixing Finding 2.\n\n### Acceptance Criteria\n\n- [ ] Placeholder content `\"[Voice memo - transcribing...]\"` is never embedded\n- [ ] Placeholder content is never sent to Claude for auto-organization\n- [ ] Successful late transcription triggers re-embedding and re-tagging\n- [ ] The `audio_pending/{id}.webm` file is cleaned up after successful transcription\n\n---\n\n## Finding 4: Background Queue Backpressure\n\n**Severity**: MEDIUM\n**Category**: Availability\n**Affected files**:\n- `src/background/mod.rs:23` (channel capacity)\n- `src/background/mod.rs:57-62` (enqueue method)\n- `src/routes/notes.rs:174-177` (create_note enqueue)\n- Various batch import endpoints that enqueue in loops\n\n### Problem Statement\n\nThe background processor uses a single `mpsc::channel(100)` for all job types. The `enqueue()` method calls `self.sender.send()`, which is an `async` operation that **blocks when the channel is full** (at 100 pending jobs).\n\nDuring a batch import (e.g., importing 1000 bookmarks), each imported note calls `enqueue(id)`. After the first 100 enqueues, subsequent calls block the HTTP handler's async task until the background processor drains the channel. Since each `ProcessNote` job makes 2-3 external API calls (Ollama + Claude), draining one slot takes several seconds.\n\n### Impact\n\n- **HTTP request timeouts**: A batch import of 1000 notes could take hours to complete from the caller's perspective, as each `enqueue` after the first 100 blocks for seconds.\n- **Request stacking**: During the blocked period, other HTTP requests sharing the same Tokio runtime continue to be scheduled, but any request that also tries to enqueue (e.g., a user creating a note while a batch import is running) will also block.\n- **Audio generation starvation**: Since `ProcessNote` and `GenerateAudio` share the same channel and processor, a large batch import prevents any audio generation until all notes are processed.\n\n### Root Cause\n\nThe architecture uses a single bounded channel for all background work, processed sequentially by a single consumer task. This was appropriate for the initial use case (one user creating notes one at a time) but doesn't scale to batch operations.\n\n### Proposed Fix\n\n**Option A: Non-blocking enqueue (simplest)**\n\nChange `enqueue` to use `try_send` and log a warning when the channel is full, rather than blocking:\n\n```rust\npub fn enqueue(&self, note_id: i64) -> Result<()> {\n    match self.sender.try_send(BackgroundJob::ProcessNote(note_id)) {\n        Ok(()) => Ok(()),\n        Err(mpsc::error::TrySendError::Full(_)) => {\n            warn!(note_id, \"Background queue full, note will be picked up on next startup via rederive_queue\");\n            Ok(())\n        }\n        Err(e) => Err(anyhow::anyhow!(\"Background channel closed: {e}\")),\n    }\n}\n```\n\nThis works because `rederive_queue` on startup already picks up any notes that were never embedded.\n\n**Option B: Separate queues (more work, better isolation)**\n\nUse separate channels for `ProcessNote` and `GenerateAudio`, each with their own consumer task. This prevents note processing from starving audio generation.\n\n### Acceptance Criteria\n\n- [ ] Batch imports of 1000+ notes do not block HTTP responses\n- [ ] Notes that overflow the channel are eventually processed (via `rederive_queue` or a periodic sweep)\n- [ ] Audio generation is not starved by large note processing backlogs\n\n---\n\n## Finding 5: Podcast Feed Port Mismatch\n\n**Severity**: MEDIUM\n**Category**: Functionality\n**Affected files**:\n- `src/routes/audio.rs:399-402` (podcast_feed handler)\n- `src/main.rs:81-84` (server port binding)\n\n### Problem Statement\n\nThe podcast feed handler defaults to port `8999` for audio enclosure URLs:\n\n```rust\n// src/routes/audio.rs:400\nlet port = std::env::var(\"NOTE_PORT\").unwrap_or_else(|_| \"8999\".to_string());\n```\n\nBut the server binds to port `9999` by default:\n\n```rust\n// src/main.rs:81-82\nlet port: u16 = env::var(\"NOTE_PORT\")\n    .unwrap_or_else(|_| \"9999\".to_string())\n```\n\nWhen `NOTE_PORT` is not set (the common development case), the RSS feed generates audio URLs pointing to `http://localhost:8999/api/audio/episodes/.../file` while the server is actually running on `http://localhost:9999`.\n\n### Impact\n\nPodcast clients (Apple Podcasts, Overcast, etc.) subscribing to the RSS feed will get connection refused errors when trying to download or stream audio episodes. The feed itself loads fine (it's served from the correct port), but all `<enclosure>` URLs point to the wrong port.\n\n### Root Cause\n\nA likely typo or copy-paste error. The `audio.rs` file was added later and the default port was not synchronized with `main.rs`.\n\n### Proposed Fix\n\nChange `audio.rs:400` from `\"8999\"` to `\"9999\"`:\n\n```rust\nlet port = std::env::var(\"NOTE_PORT\").unwrap_or_else(|_| \"9999\".to_string());\n```\n\nOr better, extract the default port to a constant shared between `main.rs` and `audio.rs`.\n\n### Acceptance Criteria\n\n- [ ] RSS feed enclosure URLs match the server's listening port\n- [ ] Default port constant is defined in one place\n\n---\n\n## Finding 6: No Frontend Notification of AI Enrichment\n\n**Severity**: MEDIUM\n**Category**: User Experience\n**Affected files**:\n- `src/routes/notes.rs:135-179` (create_note)\n- `src/background/mod.rs:89-119` (process_note)\n- `web/src/App.tsx:82-92` (note creation flow)\n\n### Problem Statement\n\nWhen a user creates a note, the frontend receives the bare note immediately (no title, no summary, no tags) and refreshes the note list. The background processor then asynchronously enriches the note with AI-generated metadata via Ollama and Claude. There is no mechanism (WebSocket, SSE, polling) to notify the frontend when enrichment completes.\n\n### Impact\n\n- Users see their newly created notes without titles, summaries, or tags\n- First-time users may believe AI features are broken\n- The only way to see enriched metadata is to manually reload or create another note (which triggers `loadNotes`)\n- For voice memos where transcription is pending, the note shows `\"[Voice memo - transcribing...]\"` indefinitely in the current view\n\n### Proposed Fix\n\n**Option A: Polling (simplest)**\n\nAfter creating a note, the frontend polls `GET /api/notes/:id` every 2-3 seconds (up to 30 seconds) until `title` is non-null, then refreshes the display.\n\n**Option B: SSE endpoint (better UX)**\n\nAdd a `GET /api/notes/:id/events` SSE endpoint that emits events when enrichment steps complete:\n\n```\nevent: enriched\ndata: {\"title\": \"...\", \"summary\": \"...\", \"tags\": [...]}\n```\n\n### Acceptance Criteria\n\n- [ ] Frontend displays AI-generated title and tags without manual reload\n- [ ] Enrichment notification occurs within 5 seconds of background processing completion\n\n---\n\n## Finding 7: Audio-Note Temporal Coupling\n\n**Severity**: LOW\n**Category**: Fragile Coupling\n**Affected files**:\n- `src/background/tts.rs:74-80` (content_mode summary fallback)\n- `src/background/auto_org.rs:67-84` (summary generation)\n- `src/background/mod.rs:29-49` (sequential FIFO processing)\n\n### Problem Statement\n\nWhen generating audio in `content_mode: \"summary\"`, the TTS pipeline reads `note.summary`:\n\n```rust\n// src/background/tts.rs:75-78\nlet text = if episode.content_mode == \"summary\" {\n    note.summary.as_deref().unwrap_or(&note.content)\n} else {\n    &note.content\n};\n```\n\nThe `summary` field is populated by `auto_org_note()` during background processing. This creates a temporal dependency: summary mode TTS requires that auto_org has already run for the target notes.\n\n### Why It Works Today\n\nBoth `ProcessNote` and `GenerateAudio` go through the same sequential FIFO channel. A note created before an audio episode is requested will have its `ProcessNote` job processed first, populating the summary before `GenerateAudio` runs.\n\n### Why It's Fragile\n\nThis ordering guarantee is **implicit** — it depends on the single-channel, single-consumer architecture. If the processor is ever made concurrent (separate channels, multiple consumers, or a thread pool), this guarantee breaks. The TTS system would silently fall back to full content without any warning.\n\n### Proposed Fix\n\nNo code change needed now, but add a documentation comment in both `tts.rs` and `mod.rs` explaining this dependency. If concurrency is ever added, add an explicit check in the TTS pipeline that waits for or verifies that auto_org has completed for the target notes.\n\n---\n\n## Finding 8: Delete Orphan Cascade\n\n**Severity**: LOW\n**Category**: Disk Cleanup\n**Affected files**:\n- `src/db/queries.rs:73-94` (delete_note)\n- `src/db/migrations.rs` (audio_episode_notes schema)\n\n### Problem Statement\n\nWhen a note is deleted:\n\n1. `delete_note()` removes rows from `note_tags`, `note_embeddings`, `note_links`, and `notes`\n2. `audio_episode_notes` has `ON DELETE CASCADE` on the `note_id` foreign key, so the junction row is removed (but only if PRAGMA foreign_keys is ON — see Finding 1)\n3. If the deleted note was the **only** note linked to an audio episode, the `audio_episodes` row persists with zero linked notes\n4. The audio file on disk (`audio/{episode_id}.mp3`) persists forever\n\nAdditionally, if a `ProcessNote` job is in the background queue for a deleted note, `get_note(conn, note_id)` returns an error. This error is logged and swallowed (harmless but noisy).\n\n### Impact\n\nOver time, orphaned audio episodes and their MP3 files accumulate on disk. No user-visible effect other than wasted storage.\n\n### Proposed Fix\n\nIn `delete_note`, after deleting the note, check if any audio episodes now have zero linked notes and clean them up:\n\n```sql\nDELETE FROM audio_episodes\nWHERE id NOT IN (SELECT DISTINCT episode_id FROM audio_episode_notes);\n```\n\nAlso delete the corresponding `audio/{episode_id}.mp3` files from disk.\n\n---\n\n## Finding 9: Pagination Count Mismatch\n\n**Severity**: LOW\n**Category**: UX Consistency\n**Affected files**:\n- `src/routes/notes.rs:260-340` (list_notes handler)\n\n### Problem Statement\n\nThe `list_notes` handler has two code paths with inconsistent `count` behavior:\n\n**Path 1: With search query (line 265-308)**\n```rust\n// Filters notes in memory after fetching, sets count = filtered.len()\nlet count = notes.len() as i64;\n```\n\n**Path 2: Without search query (line 309-340)**\n```rust\n// Filters notes in memory after fetching, but sets count = total from DB\nlet total = flatten_interact(... queries::count_notes(conn) ...)?;\n// count: total  ← this is the TOTAL count, ignoring the exclude_tag filter\n```\n\nWhen `hideImportedItems` is enabled (exclude_tag = \"hidden\"), Path 2 returns `count: total_notes_in_db` but the `notes` array has fewer items (hidden notes removed). The frontend cannot correctly implement \"showing X of Y notes\" or pagination.\n\n### Additionally\n\nBoth paths fetch `limit` notes and then filter in memory. If 20 notes are fetched and 15 are hidden, only 5 are returned — fewer than `limit`. The `random_notes` endpoint handles this correctly by applying the exclusion in SQL.\n\n### Proposed Fix\n\nApply the `exclude_tag` filter in the SQL query (like `random_notes` does) rather than in memory. This ensures `count` matches the filtered result set and `limit` returns the expected number of items.\n\n---\n\n## Finding 10: Dual AppError Response Formats\n\n**Severity**: LOW\n**Category**: API Consistency\n**Affected files**:\n- `src/routes/notes.rs:526-547` (AppError — JSON responses)\n- `src/routes/ingest.rs:647-668` (AppError — plain text responses)\n\n### Problem Statement\n\nTwo independent `AppError` enums exist with identical variants (`BadRequest(String)`, `Internal(anyhow::Error)`) but different response formats:\n\n```rust\n// notes.rs:539 — returns JSON\n(status, Json(serde_json::json!({ \"error\": message }))).into_response()\n\n// ingest.rs:656-658 — returns plain text\n(StatusCode::BAD_REQUEST, msg).into_response()\n```\n\nThe frontend's `apiFetch` does `await res.text()` and throws the result as an error message. Ingest errors appear as raw text (\"Content cannot be empty\") while note errors appear as JSON strings (`{\"error\":\"Content cannot be empty\"}`).\n\n### Proposed Fix\n\nExtract `AppError` into a shared module (e.g., `src/error.rs`) and use it across all route modules. All error responses should return consistent JSON.\n\n---\n\n## Finding 11: TTS Temp File Name Collisions\n\n**Severity**: LOW\n**Category**: Robustness\n**Affected files**:\n- `src/background/tts.rs:324-327` (pcm_to_mp3)\n- `src/background/tts.rs:455` (concat_list)\n\n### Problem Statement\n\nTemp files use `std::process::id()` for naming:\n\n```rust\nlet pcm_path = tmp_dir.join(format!(\"tts_pcm_{}.raw\", std::process::id()));\nlet mp3_path = tmp_dir.join(format!(\"tts_mp3_{}.mp3\", std::process::id()));\n```\n\nThe PID is constant for the entire server lifetime. If the processor were ever made concurrent, two simultaneous audio generation jobs would write to the same temp files. Even in the current sequential model, if an error leaves a temp file behind, it persists with the same name and could contain stale data for the next conversion.\n\n### Proposed Fix\n\nReplace `std::process::id()` with `uuid::Uuid::new_v4()` or use `tempfile::NamedTempFile` for automatic cleanup.\n\n---\n\n## Finding 12: Approximate Date Calculation\n\n**Severity**: LOW\n**Category**: Display Bug\n**Affected files**:\n- `src/routes/audio.rs:495-508` (chrono_today function)\n\n### Problem Statement\n\nThe `chrono_today()` function uses a naive date calculation:\n\n```rust\nlet days = epoch_secs / 86400;\nlet year = 1970 + days / 365;\nlet remaining_days = days % 365;\nlet month = remaining_days / 30 + 1;\nlet day = remaining_days % 30 + 1;\n```\n\nThis doesn't account for leap years (14 since 1970, so ~14 days of accumulated drift). Used for digest episode titles like \"2026-02-14 Daily Digest\".\n\n### Proposed Fix\n\nUse `time::OffsetDateTime::now_utc()` from the `time` crate (already in scope via `rss`), or add `chrono` as a dependency.\n\n---\n\n## Priority Matrix\n\n```\n            IMPACT\n     LOW    MEDIUM    HIGH    CRITICAL\n   ┌───────┬─────────┬───────┬──────────┐\nH  │       │ #4 #6   │ #2 #3 │   #1     │  ← Fix first\nI  │       │         │       │          │\nG  ├───────┼─────────┼───────┼──────────┤\nH  │       │ #5      │       │          │\n   ├───────┼─────────┼───────┼──────────┤\n   │ #7 #8 │ #9 #10  │       │          │\nL  │#11#12 │         │       │          │  ← Fix later\nO  └───────┴─────────┴───────┴──────────┘\nW          EFFORT\n```\n\n---\n\n## Implementation Roadmap\n\n### Phase 1: Critical Data Integrity (Immediate)\n\n| # | Finding | Est. Scope | Dependencies |\n|---|---------|------------|--------------|\n| 1 | Connection pool PRAGMA leak | ~20 LoC change in `db/mod.rs`, update all `pool.get()` call sites | None |\n\n### Phase 2: Data Consistency (Next Sprint)\n\n| # | Finding | Est. Scope | Dependencies |\n|---|---------|------------|--------------|\n| 2 | Stale embeddings after update | Add `force` param to BackgroundJob, modify embed.rs and auto_org.rs guards | None |\n| 3 | Voice memo garbage embeddings | Add content check in process_note, update retry_pending_transcription | Finding 2 |\n| 5 | Podcast feed port mismatch | 1-line fix | None |\n\n### Phase 3: UX & Robustness (Following Sprint)\n\n| # | Finding | Est. Scope | Dependencies |\n|---|---------|------------|--------------|\n| 4 | Background queue backpressure | Change to try_send, rely on rederive_queue | None |\n| 6 | No enrichment notification | Add polling or SSE endpoint | None |\n| 9 | Pagination count mismatch | Move exclude_tag filter to SQL | None |\n| 10 | Dual AppError formats | Extract shared error module | None |\n\n### Phase 4: Cleanup (Backlog)\n\n| # | Finding | Est. Scope | Dependencies |\n|---|---------|------------|--------------|\n| 7 | Audio-note temporal coupling | Add comments documenting the dependency | None |\n| 8 | Delete orphan cascade | Add cleanup query in delete_note | Finding 1 (needs FK) |\n| 11 | TTS temp file collisions | Replace PID with UUID | None |\n| 12 | Approximate date calculation | Use `time` crate | None |\n",
